The Love Alliance, a new five-year programme (2021-2025), is based on an unwavering commitment to protecting, promoting and fulfilling sexual and reproductive health and rights (SRHR) globally, unifying people who use drugs, sex workers and LGBTIQ+ movements, and amplifying the diversity of voices in these communities.

Funded by the Dutch Ministry of Foreign Affairs, the Love Alliance brings together national thought leaders GALZ, SANPUD and Sisonke, regional grantmakers UHAI EASHRI, AFE and ISDAO, with the global network of people living with HIV (GNP+) and the Netherlands-based administrative lead Aidsfonds. 

Together, we advocate for adequate levels of funding and for taking truly human rights-based programmes to scale. We take this opportunity to prioritise and invest in challenging the structural barriers of underfunding, criminalisation and exclusion of us in all our diversity.

The International HIV/AIDS Alliance (IHAA) is an alliance partner within the Beat the AIDS Epidemic partnership. This strategic partnership aims to beat the AIDS epidemic in countries that are most affected by HIV. In these countries we will strengthen local civil society organisations to advocate for equal access to HIV and sexual and reproductive health-related services; equal sexual and reproductive health and rights for those most affected by HIV; and decriminalisation, particularly for key populations. We will build new coalitions and bring local evidence to global policy development level.
No patients will be directly affected by this study.

- Reduced vulnerability to HIV/AIDS and susceptibility to its social and economic impacts
- Improved livelihood options and income opportunities created for vulnerable groups mainly women and  youth
- CBOs are able to effectively engage in HIV prevention and impact mitigation initiatives

Get Up Speak Out builds on the previous Access, Knowledge and Services (ASK) and Unite for Body Rights (UfBR) projects, which were implemented in the same countries through alliances of complementing partners.  
 
The project aims to improve the poor sexual and reproductive health and rights of young people by strengthening civil society organisations to effectively address young people’s rights and needs. Meaningful youth participation is a key strategy to make sure the voice of young people is heard.

ARF operates in a complex social and epidemiological environment. As of December 2016, the number of PLHIV in Russia reached 1,114,815 (official data from the Federal AIDS Center; the real number is estimated at least twice as much). In the past few years HIV incidence has been growing at 10% per year. Unsafe injecting still fuels the epidemic (52.8% of all new cases in 2016), and heterosexual transmission is on the increase. PLHIV lack access to antiretrovirals (according to the MoH only 30% of PLHIV in need were receiving them). In spite of the grim statistics, the Russian government vigorously opposes harm reduction programs and creates obstacles to NGOs doing HIV prevention among key affected populations. Prevention was until recently almost entirely funded by international donors and the current HIV strategy accepted by the Ministry of Health does not envision harm reduction. At the end of 2017 the core funding for our harm reduction project – the Global Fund HIV grant– is coming to an end and no extension of it is expected (Russia is not eligible for GF HIV or TB grants anymore). This could have serious consequences for the harm reduction services we provide to PWUD on the streets of Moscow as if we will not manage to find alternative sources of funding it means a termination of our key services and losing a great number of our experienced staff. 
The funds for the legal and human rights advocacy are still sustained, but also under threat if service delivery will be interrupted or stopped.

1. City administration signed on to the Paris Declaration (and joined the Zero TB Cities Initiative, if the scope of work permits), including commitment and action plan to achieve 90-90-90 targets, particularly among the key populations.
2. Key populations included as priority groups and partners/service providers in the municipal plans; and the progress on key populations’ related targets tracked.
3. Increased city funding and endorsed HIV (and TB, if the scope of work permits) city improvement plan/s to strengthen response among the key populations.
4. Strengthened partnership between municipal government and NGOs, including key populations representatives on relevant city coordination group/s.
5. Strengthened advocacy capacity among representatives of the key populations communities, particularly new leaders, to effectively collaborate with municipal government, across the key populations groups, as well as with public health, human rights and other organisations relevant to the HIV/AIDS (and, where feasible, TB) response.

AFEW International and partners EVA, St. Petersburg and AFEW Kyrgyzstan, Bishkek; co–created a project strengthening civil society (CS) engagement with receptive public officials (city administration, politicians, health, law enforcement, finance). The project builds CS advocacy and influencing skills to engage with existing decision-makers and enlarge this pool of supporters at municipal level, contributing to strengthened political commitment and endorsement of international protocols on Key Population (KP) HIV services/budgeting. There is a cross-cutting focus on adolescent girls and young women (AGYW) as a priority group impacted by specific HIV drivers. The project leverages increasing responsibility at municipal level leading on HIV and health initiatives, balancing community activism with nuanced diplomacy to effect change.

With the proposed activities, IFRC and Red Cross Red Crescent National Societies of the CIS will engage civil society organizations and representatives of key populations to create a common platform for a professional dialogue with CIS parliamentarians, the Eurasian Economic Union, the Secretariat of the CIS, state health institutions, academic
communities, as well as mass media with the aim to develop and adopt model legislation, creating friendly  environment for people living with HIV (PLWHIV), reducing stigma and discrimination, and ensuring better access to
HIV-related services.

This outcome focuses on the experiences of PITCH partners when engaging advocacy targets that can influence decision-making processes. These advocacy targets will be global, regional, national, or local government representatives and politicians, as well as religious and traditional leaders and the police etc. We are looking for evidence of these advocacy targets listening to local and national civil society, including youth and KP-led organisations. We are also looking for evidence of these advocacy targets amending or introducing new policies and encouraging practice and behaviour that responds to the needs and rights of KPs and AGYW. Moreover, we are looking to draw connections between the increased capacity of PITCH partners and the effective engagement of these advocacy targets.

This outcome focuses on demonstrating increased capacity among PITCH partners to collect and use evidence (e.g. through reviews of reports
and other public documents, research using interviews and surveys, capturing data through monitoring activities etc) to inform their advocacy. It is
important that the focus of partners' reporting is on explaining in what ways their capacity to document evidence has improved, and what they have done
with this evidence. This should be described and analysed by partners from the perspective of planning and implementing their advocacy. Where partners
feel that their evidence-based advocacy has contributed toward a change in policy, when reporting against the indicators below, please provide evidence
that illustrates how your advocacy contributed to this policy change.

This outcome is concerned with achieving a long-term increase in the influence of civil society over government policy and funding of the national HIV response and, fundamentally, a reduction in barriers faced by Key Populations and AGYW to accessing services. Through this outcome PITCH will seek to achieve increased political commitment for HIV and SRHR services that target KPs and AGYW, and to develop the capacity of PITCH country partners to hold governments to account for the implementation of policies and other political commitments at all levels. With this outcome we hope to achieve a more informed and organised movement of community-led CSOs (KPs and AGYW) working together and engaging decision/opinion/policy makers, health care providers, religious leaders etc towards improving HIV and SRHR services (including implementation â€“ funding, decriminalization, promoting harm reduction) for KPs and AGYW.

For this outcome Stigma refers to both the internal stigma (self-stigma) experienced and expressed by KPs and AGYW themselves, as well as
external stigma and discrimination expressed by decision makers and those with widespread influence (government, media etc) as well as communities,
religious and traditional leaders, service providers, families etc toward KPs and AGYW. This outcome focuses on achieving changes in the beliefs, attitudes
and behaviour of those who express this external stigma and discrimination, in the hope that KPs and AGYW experience less stigma and discrimination
because of their HIV status and/or gender and sexuality over the course of PITCH. Our assumption is that as levels of external stigma reduce, incidences of
self-stigma also reduce, contributing to an increase in public demand for access to HIV-related services for KPs and AGYW.

This outcome is designed to track the progress of PITCH partners in increasing their level of interaction with national level CSOs; social
justice networks; local, district and national level authorities; and international organisations including AU, UNAIDS, Global Fund, and WHO. We are
looking to better understand how PITCH is having an impact on the ability of partners to confidently engage in dialogue and collaborate with a range of
stakeholders that have an influence over changes in policy and practice in relations to meeting the needs of KPS and AGYW. Changes in the levels of
interaction are measured through the number of meetings etc between implementing partners and the stakeholders referred to here where advocacy is
carried out. Through this outcome we also seek to understand changes in the level of capacity and confidence to advocate with country, regional and
global level advocacy targets, and the impact this has on changes in levels of engagement between PITCH partners and these same stakeholders.

Accountability is limited by government instability; systematic monitoring of access is currently insufficient, but the Technical Support Committee under NAC is envisioned to play an increasing role in this area.

At the global level, there is some limited experience using accountability mechanisms for SRHR but a more concerted, structured approach is needed in order to support key population movements to move into this space.

Currently there is no functioning human rights accountability mechanism at the national level, and efforts to scale up community-led monitoring are underway, but focus on HIV-related services (not SRHR independently).
Systematic accountability for SRHR is limited, though the Key Populations TWG provides a venue for raising some SRHR issues.

To assess the impact of lobby and advocacy programme activities on the environment for sex work. This includes monitoring a shift in practice both with positive and negative outcomes. Improved practice refers to policies and laws supportive of the wellbeing and rights of sex workers, regardless of their gender.

Male sex workers are yet to be  identified. We believe the hot spot mapping exercise that will be done this year will assist us in identifying them. Furthermore we hope to recruit one to be a peer outreach worker.
The sex workers who accessed psychosocial support services were the survivors of violence as well as other who had requested the services of the in- house counsellor.
SWs were able to access support after violence, this includes all genders and ages.
These are sex workers who were assisted to report their cases by paralegals as well as those who were given access to a lawyer, supported by HandsOFF2.
This number includes sex workers who have been reached with coffee mornings, heath and rights literacy trainings, rapid response and rights education during the sex worker household relief programme.

These are sex workers below the age of 24 years, who have been assisted by the rapid response team and peer educators. The assistance here includes referral for medical assistance to a private or public institution (where possible) however during this reporting period, accessing health care services at a public health care facility has been very difficult due to on going strikes by public healthcare workers.

These are sex workers who have attended various meetings including coffe mornings, rights literacy trainings and meetings on the decriminalization of sex workas well as well as those who were reached during the sex worker household relief programme.
